author: wsjcom
title: A Last Stand for the Golden Age of Men’s Tennis
text:
Since 2005, when Rafael Nadal won his first Grand Slam title at the French Open, men’s tennis has been dominated by five players. From then until now, the fabulous five—Nadal, Roger Federer, Novak Djokovic, Andy Murray and Stan Wawrinka—have won 50 Grand Slams. Other men have won just two.
When you look at that on paper, it seems like a mistake, an impossible feat. It has lasted longer than anyone could have imagined, and more than any of those players could have hoped. But as the French Open is set to begin this weekend...
